¬ß Why ‚¶â
¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ What are numbers? ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We want to count, forever. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Does a set exist which contains zero, and one, and two,
    and three, and all the rest? ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬ß Definition ‚¶â
¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ In‚ê£
    <a href='/sheets/successor_sets.html'>
      ‚Äñ Successor Sets ‚¶â
    </a>
    , we said ‚Äúand we continue as usual using the English
    language...‚Äù in our definition of zero, and one and two and
    three. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Can this really be carried on and on? ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We will say yes. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We will say that there exists a set which contains zero
    and contains the successor of each of its elements. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  <statement type='principle' text='Natural Numbers'>
    ‚Äñ A set which contains 0 and contains the successor of each
      of its elements exists. ‚¶â
  </statement>

  ‚Äñ This principle is sometimes called the ‚ù¨principle of
    infinity‚ù≠ (or ‚ù¨axiom of infinity‚ù≠). ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ We want this set to be unique. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ The principle says one successor set exists, but not that
    it is unique. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ To see that it is unique, notice that the intersection of
    a nonempty family of successor sets is a successor set.
    ‚Ä† ‚¶ä
      ‚Äñ This account will be expanded in future editions. ‚¶â
    ‚¶â‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Consider the intersection of the family of all successor
    sets. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ The intersection is nonempty by the principle of infinity
    (see‚ê£
    <a href='/sheets/intersection_of_empty_set.html'>
      ‚Äñ Intersection of Empty Set ‚¶â
    </a>
    ‚ê£for this subtlety). ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ The principle of extension guarantees that this intersection,
    which is a successor set contained in every other successor
    set, is unique. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We summarize: ‚¶â
‚¶â

<statement id='natural_numbers:proposition:omega' type='proposition' text='Minimal Successor Set'>
  ‚Äñ There exists a unique smallest successor set. ‚¶â
</statement>
¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ The ‚ù¨set of natural numbers‚ù≠ is the minimal successor set. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ A ‚ù¨natural number‚ù≠ (or ‚ù¨number‚ù≠, ‚ù¨natural‚ù≠) is an element of
    this minimal successor set. ‚¶â
‚¶â

